track_notes:
Follow the track through the woods, past the lodge and exit onto the mountain. There is no path / trail to the summit, so make your way upward, following the ridge as best you can. Aim for the burned heather. There are several false summits en route, and the going is rough underfoot. The last false summit is quite steep. Once you reach the top, veer right keeping to the Northern side of the east / west ridge to avoid the worst of the peat hags, which are tricky.  Make your way upward to the summit, which has a trig marker and is wide open. There is good mobile signal at the summit. Its a long hike, 7.5K and took 2 1/2 hours.
I wouldnt choose this route again, but would go via the right of the woods.
track_title: Approach from the left of Glengarra wood

track_notes:
This was the return route of the left approach, but is an easier option for climbing also. 
Cross the small pedestrian bridge at the top of the carpark and make your way upwards through woods onto the road to the water treatment plant. Follow this road up past the water tanks, climbing over a gate en route out into the forest. At the end of the road, follow a muddy track to a gate and exit onto the mountain. There is not path / trail to the summit and the going is rough underfoot. There is a deep gully after about 100m, but veer right and you will find a way down and back up again. Veering left, make your way as best you can to the summit. There are no peat hags on this route and the climb is more even. Both left and right approaches have similar uneven ground, but the slope on the right approach is more even.
Its a 6.3 K climb that took me 1:38 to descend, so would probably be climbed in around 2 hours.
track_title: Greenane south approach via the right of Glengarra woods

track_notes: Heres one route that takes in Cush and Greenane. Starting at the Galtytmore North car park,its about an hour to Cush, with a steep climb near the summit. Carry on to descend Cush heading for Galtybeg - another steep climb, turning right to Greenane. There is no track as such and lots of peat hags, so navigate as best you can. Its another 2.5 hours to Greenane. If you dont fancy returning the same route as outward and avoiding those two steep descents, you can return via Lough Muskry and follow the road back to your origin. Another 3.45 hours. 7.5 hours in total and 24Km travelling
track_title: The long way round to Greenane
